    <exercise>
    <p> [Problem A] Use the terminolgy introduced in Section 2.7 regarding the fibres of a function. 
    </p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      Define <m>v\colon\mathbb R\to\mathbb R</m> by <m>v(x)=|x|</m>.  Determine all the fibres of <m>v</m>. Is the empty set a fibre? 
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Define <m>f\colon\mathbb R\times\mathbb R\to\mathbb R</m> by <m>f(x,y)=y-x</m>.  
       Sketch four distinct fibres of <m>f</m> in the coordinate plane.
       (This makes sense because each fibre of <m>f</m> is a subset of the
       domain of <m>f</m>, and the domain of this <m>f</m> is <m>\mathbb R\times\mathbb R</m>,
       i.e. the coordinate plane.)
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <p>
        [Problem B] 
        Let <m>G</m> be a group and let <m>H</m> and <m>K</m> be subgroups of <m>G</m>. Assume <m>|H|=p</m> and <m>|K|=q</m>, where <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are prime numbers. 
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>p\ne q</m>, prove <m>H\cap K=\{1\}</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
           If <m>p=q</m>, prove <m>H=K</m> or  <m>H\cap K=\{1\}</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>    
  </exercise>

  <hint>
    <p>
      You may assume known that the intersection of two subgroups is a subgroup. Use Lagrange's Theorem.
    </p>
  </hint>
  <exercise>
    <p>
      [Problem C]  Let <m>G</m> be a group, possibly infinite, and <m>H</m> a subgroup. Let <m>\mathcal A</m> denote the set of left cosets of <m>H</m> and let <m>\mathcal B</m> denote the set of right cosets.
       (These sets could be infinite too). Define <m>f\colon \mathcal A\to \mathcal B</m> by  
    </p>
<me>
f(gH)=Hg^{-1} \qquad \text{ for all }  g\in G 
</me>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      Prove that <m>f</m> is a function (that is, prove <m>f</m> is well-defined). 
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
     Prove that <m>f</m> is bijective. (This implies that <m>|\mathcal A|=|\mathcal B|</m> and thus the number of left cosets equals the number of right cosets.) 
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</exercise>
